lescence of several different Old English personal names: <i>Æthelstān</i> ‘noble stone’, <i>Ælfstān</i> ‘elf stone’, <i>Ealdstān</i> ‘old stone’, or <i>Ealhstān</i> ‘temple stone’.","habitational name from any of various places called Alston (in Cumbria, Lancashire, Devon, and Somerset) or Alstone (in Gloucestershire and Staffordshire). With the exception of Alston in Cumbria, which is formed with the Old Norse personal name <i>Halfdan</i>, these placenames all consist of an Old English personal name + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’, for example <i>Ælfsige</i> in the case of Alstone in Gloucestershire."],"variants":[{"name":"Aston","meanings":["English:","from the Middle English personal name <i>Ad(e)stan</i>, which is usually from Old English <i>Æthelstān</i> (see   Alston  ). It may also be from the much rarer Old English name <i>Ēadstān</i>.","habitational name from any of several places in England called Aston. Most were named with Old English <i>ēast</i> ‘east’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement’. In a few cases the first element is <i>æsc</i> ‘ash tree’."]},{"name":"Allston","meanings":["English: variant of   Alston  ."]},{"name":"Hailstone","meanings":["habitational name from Hailstone Hill in Wiltshire or Hailstone Farm in Gloucestershire, the former of which may be derived from Old English <i>hālig-stān</i> ‘holy stone’ or <i>hagolstān</i> ‘hailstone’ (Middle English <i>hawelston</i>, <i>hailston</i>).","from <i>Ailstan</i>, a variant of the Old English personal name <i>Æthelstān</i> (‘noble’ + ‘stone’), with prosthetic initial <i>H-</i>. The first element of the Old English name developed from <i>Æthel-</i> to <i>Ægel-</i> and then to <i>Ail-</i>; it was often further shortened to <i>Al-</i> (see   Alston  ).","English:"]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":3,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":28,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":41,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":50,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":95,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Alston was born in 1287, in Stisted, Essex, England as the son of Edward Alston. He married Ann Symons in Guilden Morden, C